1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,560
Pandas is a powerful tool for data analysis and manipulation.

2

00:00:04,560  -->  00:00:11,820
One of the most popular formats used to store data is CSV or comma-separated values.

3

00:00:11,820  -->  00:00:17,585
We can load CSV files into data frames using the read.csv() function.

4

00:00:17,585  -->  00:00:21,000
Let's load Google stock data into a data frame.

5

00:00:21,000  -->  00:00:27,195
This file was taken from Yahoo Finances and contains Google stock data from August 19th,

6

00:00:27,195  -->  00:00:31,055
2004 to October 13th, 2017.

7

00:00:31,055  -->  00:00:36,710
The data frame consists of 3,313 rows and seven columns.

8

00:00:36,710  -->  00:00:38,650
Let's look at the stock data.

9

00:00:38,650  -->  00:00:41,550
We can see it's a pretty large dataset and that

10

00:00:41,550  -->  00:00:46,070
pandas automatically assign numerical row indices to the data frame.

11

00:00:46,070  -->  00:00:51,790
Pandas also used the names that appeared in the CSV file to assign the column labels.

12

00:00:51,790  -->  00:00:54,630
When dealing with large datasets like this one,

13

00:00:54,630  -->  00:00:57,250
it's often useful to just take a look at

14

00:00:57,250  -->  00:01:00,540
the first few rows of data instead of the whole dataset.

15

00:01:00,540  -->  00:01:04,470
We can take a look at the first five rows using the HEAD method.

16

00:01:04,470  -->  00:01:09,520
We can also take a look at the last five rows of data using the TAIL method.

17

00:01:09,520  -->  00:01:12,460
Both of these accept an integer as an argument

18

00:01:12,460  -->  00:01:15,880
if you want to specify a different number of rows to return.

19

00:01:15,880  -->  00:01:21,400
For example, I can get the last eight rows like this or the first two rows like this.

20

00:01:21,400  -->  00:01:26,220
Let's do a quick check to see whether we have any non-values in this data set.

21

00:01:26,220  -->  00:01:29,960
To do so, we will use the ISNULL() method followed by

22

00:01:29,960  -->  00:01:34,305
the any() method to check whether any of the columns contain non-values.

23

00:01:34,305  -->  00:01:36,980
This shows us that we have no missing data.

24

00:01:36,980  -->  00:01:39,100
When dealing with large datasets,

25

00:01:39,100  -->  00:01:42,600
it's often useful to get statistical information from them.

26

00:01:42,600  -->  00:01:46,020
Pandas provides a described method which returns

27

00:01:46,020  -->  00:01:49,700
descriptive statistics on each column of the data frame.

28

00:01:49,700  -->  00:01:54,145
We can access elements in a data frame in different ways.

29

00:01:54,145  -->  00:01:57,945
In general, we can access rows, columns,

30

00:01:57,945  -->  00:02:02,480
or individual elements by using the row and column labels.

31

00:02:02,480  -->  00:02:04,300
Let's see some examples.

32

00:02:04,300  -->  00:02:07,900
We can access the bikes column using the column label like

33

00:02:07,900  -->  00:02:13,400
this and use a list of the column labels to access multiple columns.

34

00:02:13,400  -->  00:02:15,680
We can access a row using

35

00:02:15,680  -->  00:02:21,080
the row index label and the value at a specific row and column like this.

36

00:02:21,080  -->  00:02:25,820
It's important to know that when accessing individual elements in a data frame,

37

00:02:25,820  -->  00:02:27,680
like in this last example,

38

00:02:27,680  -->  00:02:31,840
the column label always comes first and then the row label.

39

00:02:31,840  -->  00:02:35,875
If you provide the row label first, you'll get an error.

40

00:02:35,875  -->  00:02:40,670
We can also modify our data frames by adding rows or columns.

41

00:02:40,670  -->  00:02:44,450
Suppose we decided to add a shirts column to our data frame.

42

00:02:44,450  -->  00:02:47,630
To do this, we can define a shirts column containing

43

00:02:47,630  -->  00:02:51,350
the quantity for each of the two store rows like this.

44

00:02:51,350  -->  00:02:55,055
This added a new column to the end of our data frame.

45

00:02:55,055  -->  00:02:57,250
We can also add new columns using

46

00:02:57,250  -->  00:03:01,270
arithmetic operations on other columns of our data frame.

47

00:03:01,270  -->  00:03:04,530
For example, we can create a new column called

48

00:03:04,530  -->  00:03:09,370
suits by computing the sum of the shirts and pants column.
